{"title_page": "List of map projections", "text_new": "{{Dynamic list}}\n\nThis is a summary of [[map projection]]s that have articles of their own on Wikipedia or that are otherwise [[WP:NOTABLE|notable]]. Because there is no limit to the number of possible map projections,<ref name=\"SnyderFlattening\">\n{{cite book\n| author=Snyder, John P.\n| title=Flattening the earth: two thousand years of map projections\n| publisher =[[University of Chicago Press]]\n| year=1993\n| isbn =0-226-76746-9\n| page=1}}\n</ref> there can be no comprehensive list.\n\n==Table of projections==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Projection\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n! Type\n! Properties\n! Creator\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Year\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|- id=\"cylindrical\"\n| [[Equirectangular projection|Equirectangular]] <br/><small>= equidistant cylindrical<br/> = rectangular<br/> = la carte parall\u00e9logrammatique</small>\n| [[File:Equirectangular projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equidistant\n| [[Marinus of Tyre]]\n| {{Circa|120|sortable=yes}}\n| Simplest geometry; distances along meridians are conserved.<br/>\n[[Plate carr\u00e9e projection|Plate carr\u00e9e]]: special case having the equator as the standard parallel.\n|-\n| [[Cassini projection|Cassini]] <br/><small>= Cassini\u2013Soldner</small>\n| [[File:Cassini projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equidistant\n| [[C\u00e9sar-Fran\u00e7ois Cassini de Thury]]\n| 1745\n| Transverse of equidistant projection; distances along central meridian are conserved.<br/>Distances perpendicular to central meridian are preserved.\n|-\n| [[Mercator projection|Mercator]]<br/><small>= Wright</small>\n| [[File:Mercator projection Square.JPG|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Conformal\n| [[Gerardus Mercator]]\n| 1569\n| Lines of constant bearing (rhumb lines) are straight, aiding navigation. Areas inflate with latitude, becoming so extreme that the map cannot show the poles.\n|-\n| [[Web Mercator]]\n| [[File:Web maps Mercator projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Google]]\n| 2005\n| Variant can\u2019t of [[Mercator projection|Mercator]] that ignores Earth's ellipticity for fast calculation, and clips latitudes to ~85.05\u00b0 for square presentation. De facto standard for Web mapping applications.\n|-\n| [[Transverse Mercator projection#Ellipsoidal transverse Mercator|Gauss\u2013Kr\u00fcger]]<br/><small>= Gauss conformal<br/>= (ellipsoidal) transverse Mercator</small>\n| [[File:Ellipsoidal transverse Mercator projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Conformal\n| [[Carl Friedrich Gauss]]\n[[Johann Heinrich Louis Kr\u00fcger]]\n| 1822\n| This transverse, ellipsoidal form of the Mercator is finite, unlike  the equatorial Mercator. Forms the basis of the [[Universal Transverse Mercator coordinate system]].\n|-\n| [[Roussilhe oblique stereographic projection|Roussilhe oblique stereographic]]\n|\n|\n|\n| Henri Roussilhe\n| 1922\n|\n|-\n|Hotine oblique Mercator\n|[[File:Hotine Mercator projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n|Cylindrical\n|Conformal\n|M. Rosenmund, J. Laborde, Martin Hotine\n|1903\n|\n|-\n| [[Gall stereographic projection|Gall stereographic]]<br/>\n| [[File:Gall Stereographic projection SW centered.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[James Gall]]\n| 1855\n| Intended to resemble the Mercator while also displaying the poles. Standard parallels at 45\u00b0N/S.\n|-\n| [[Miller projection|Miller]]<br/><small>= Miller cylindrical</small>\n| [[File:Miller projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Osborn Maitland Miller]]\n| 1942\n| Intended to resemble the Mercator while also displaying the poles.\n|-\n| [[Lambert cylindrical equal-area projection|Lambert cylindrical equal-area]]\n| [[File:Lambert cylindrical equal-area projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Johann Heinrich Lambert]]\n| 1772\n| Standard parallel at the equator. Aspect ratio of \u03c0 (3.14). Base projection of the [[cylindrical equal-area projection|cylindrical equal-area]] family.\n|-\n| [[Behrmann projection|Behrmann]]\n| [[File:Behrmann projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Walter Behrmann]]\n| 1910\n| Horizontally compressed version of the Lambert equal-area. Has standard parallels at 30\u00b0N/S and an aspect ratio of 2.36.\n|-\n| [[Hobo\u2013Dyer projection|Hobo\u2013Dyer]]\n| [[File:Hobo\u2013Dyer projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Mick Dyer]]\n| 2002\n| Horizontally compressed version of the Lambert equal-area. Very similar are Trystan Edwards and Smyth equal surface (= Craster rectangular) projections with standard parallels at around 37\u00b0N/S. Aspect ratio of ~2.0.\n|-\n| [[Gall\u2013Peters projection|Gall\u2013Peters]]<br/><small>= Gall orthographic<br/>= Peters</small>\n| [[File:Gall\u2013Peters projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[James Gall]]\n([[Arno Peters]])\n| 1855\n| Horizontally compressed version of the Lambert equal-area. Standard parallels at 45\u00b0N/S. Aspect ratio of ~1.6. Similar is Balthasart projection with standard parallels at 50\u00b0N/S.\n|-\n| [[Central cylindrical projection|Central cylindrical]]\n| [[File:Central cylindric projection square.JPG|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Perspective\n| (unknown)\n| {{Circa|1850|sortable=yes}}\n| Practically unused in cartography because of severe polar distortion, but popular in [[panoramic photography]], especially for architectural scenes.\n|- id=\"pseudocylindrical\"\n| [[Sinusoidal projection|Sinusoidal]]<br/><small>= Sanson\u2013Flamsteed<br/>= Mercator equal-area</small>\n| [[File:Sinusoidal projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area, equidistant\n| (Several; first is unknown)\n| {{Circa|1600|sortable=yes}}\n| Meridians are sinusoids; parallels are equally spaced. Aspect ratio of 2:1. Distances along parallels are conserved.\n|-\n| [[Mollweide projection|Mollweide]]<br/><small>= elliptical<br/>= Babinet<br/>= homolographic</small>\n| [[File:Mollweide projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Karl Brandan Mollweide]]\n| 1805\n| Meridians are ellipses.\n|-\n| [[Eckert II projection|Eckert II]]\n| [[File:Eckert II projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Max Eckert-Greifendorff]]\n| 1906\n|\n|-\n| [[Eckert IV projection|Eckert IV]]\n| [[File:Ecker IV projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Max Eckert-Greifendorff]]\n| 1906\n| Parallels are unequal in spacing and scale; outer meridians are semicircles; other meridians are semiellipses.\n|-\n| [[Eckert VI projection|Eckert VI]]\n| [[File:Ecker VI projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Max Eckert-Greifendorff]]\n| 1906\n| Parallels are unequal in spacing and scale; meridians are half-period sinusoids.\n|-\n| [[Ortelius oval projection|Ortelius oval]]\n| [[File:Ortelius oval projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Battista Agnese]]\n| 1540\n|\nMeridians are circular.<ref>{{cite book|author=Donald Fenna|title=Cartographic Science: A Compendium of Map Projections, with Derivations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8LZeu8RxOIsC|year=2006|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8493-8169-0|page=249}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Goode homolosine projection|Goode homolosine]]\n| [[File:Goode homolosine projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[John Paul Goode]]\n| 1923\n| Hybrid of Sinusoidal and Mollweide projections.<br/>Usually used in interrupted form.\n|-\n| [[Kavrayskiy VII projection|Kavrayskiy VII]]\n| [[File:Kavraiskiy VII projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Vladimir V. Kavrayskiy]]\n| 1939\n| Evenly spaced parallels. Equivalent to Wagner VI horizontally compressed by a factor of <small><math>\\sqrt{3}/{2}</math>.</small>\n|-\n| [[Robinson projection|Robinson]]\n| [[File:Robinson projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Arthur H. Robinson]]\n| 1963\n| Computed by interpolation of tabulated values. Used by Rand McNally since inception and used by [[National Geographic Society|NGS]] in 1988\u20131998.\n|-\n| [[Equal Earth projection|Equal Earth]]\n| [[File:Equal Earth projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| Bojan \u0160avri\u010d, Tom Patterson, Bernhard Jenny\n| 2018\n| Inspired by the Robinson projection, but retains the relative size of areas.\n|-\n| [[Natural Earth projection|Natural Earth]]\n| [[File:Natural Earth projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Tom Patterson (cartographer)|Tom Patterson]]\n| 2011\n| Computed by interpolation of tabulated values.\n|-\n| [[Tobler hyperelliptical projection|Tobler hyperelliptical]]\n| [[File:Tobler hyperelliptical projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Waldo R. Tobler]]\n| 1973\n| A family of map projections that includes as special cases Mollweide projection, Collignon projection, and the various cylindrical equal-area projections.\n|-\n| [[Wagner VI projection|Wagner VI]]\n| [[File:Wagner VI projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[K. H. Wagner]]\n| 1932\n| Equivalent to Kavrayskiy VII vertically compressed by a factor of <math>\\sqrt{3}/{2}</math>.\n|-\n| [[Collignon projection|Collignon]]\n| [[File:Collignon projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[\u00c9douard Collignon]]\n| {{Circa|1865|sortable=yes}}\n| Depending on configuration, the projection also may map the sphere to a single diamond or a pair of squares.\n|-\n| [[HEALPix]]\n| [[File:HEALPix projection SW.svg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Krzysztof M. G\u00f3rski]]\n| 1997\n| Hybrid of Collignon + Lambert cylindrical equal-area.\n|-\n| [[Boggs eumorphic projection|Boggs eumorphic]]\n| [[File:Boggs eumorphic projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| Samuel Whittemore Boggs\n| 1929\n| The equal-area projection that results from average of sinusoidal and Mollweide ''y''-coordinates and thereby constraining the ''x'' coordinate.\n|-\n| Craster parabolic <br/><small>=Putni\u0146\u0161 P4</small>\n| [[File:Craster parabolic projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| John Craster\n| 1929\n| Meridians are parabolas. Standard parallels at 36\u00b046\u2032N/S; parallels are unequal in spacing and scale; 2:1 aspect.\n|-\n| McBryde\u2013Thomas flat-pole quartic<br/><small>= McBryde\u2013Thomas #4</small>\n| [[File:McBryde-Thomas flat-pole quartic projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| Felix W. McBryde, Paul Thomas\n| 1949\n| Standard parallels at 33\u00b045\u2032N/S; parallels are unequal in spacing and scale; meridians are fourth-order curves. Distortion-free only where the standard parallels intersect the central meridian.\n|-\n| [[Quartic authalic]]\n| [[File:Quartic authalic projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| Karl Siemon\nOscar Adams\n| data-sort-value=1937 | 1937\n1944\n| Parallels are unequal in spacing and scale. No distortion along the equator. Meridians are fourth-order curves.\n|-\n| The Times\n|[[File:The Times projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Compromise\n| John Muir\n| 1965\n| Standard parallels 45\u00b0N/S. Parallels based on Gall stereographic, but with curved meridians. Developed for Bartholomew Ltd., The Times Atlas.\n|-\n| [[Loximuthal projection|Loximuthal]]\n| [[File:Loximuthal projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Compromise\n| Karl Siemon\n[[Waldo R. Tobler]]\n| data-sort-value=1935 | 1935\n1966\n| From the designated centre, lines of constant bearing (rhumb lines/loxodromes) are straight and have the correct length. Generally asymmetric about the equator.\n|-\n| [[Aitoff projection|Aitoff]]\n| [[File:Aitoff projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoazimuthal\n| Compromise\n| [[David A. Aitoff]]\n| 1889\n| Stretching of modified equatorial azimuthal equidistant map. Boundary is 2:1 ellipse. Largely superseded by Hammer.\n|-\n| [[Hammer projection|Hammer]]<br/><small>= Hammer\u2013Aitoff<br/>variations: Briesemeister; Nordic</small>\n| [[File:Hammer projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoazimuthal\n| Equal-area\n| [[Ernst Hammer (cartographer)|Ernst Hammer]]\n| 1892\n|Modified from azimuthal equal-area equatorial map. Boundary is 2:1 ellipse. Variants are oblique versions, centred on 45\u00b0N.\n|-\n| [[Strebe 1995 projection|Strebe 1995]]\n| [[File:Strebe 1995 11E SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoazimuthal\n| Equal-area\n| Daniel \"daan\" Strebe\n| 1994\n| Formulated by using other equal-area map projections as transformations.\n|-\n| [[Winkel tripel projection|Winkel tripel]]\n| [[File:Winkel triple projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoazimuthal\n| Compromise\n| [[Oswald Winkel]]\n| 1921\n| Arithmetic mean of the [[equirectangular projection]] and the [[Aitoff projection]]. Standard world projection for the [[National Geographic Society|NGS]] since 1998.\n|-\n| [[Van der Grinten projection|Van der Grinten]]\n| [[File:Van der Grinten projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Other\n| Compromise\n| [[Alphons J. van der Grinten]]\n| 1904\n| Boundary is a circle. All parallels and meridians are circular arcs. Usually clipped near 80\u00b0N/S. Standard world projection of the [[National Geographic Society|NGS]] in 1922\u20131988.\n|- id=\"conic\"\n| [[Equidistant conic projection|Equidistant conic]]<br/><small>= simple conic</small>\n| [[File:Equidistant conic projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Conic\n| Equidistant\n| Based on [[Ptolemy]]'s 1st Projection\n| {{Circa|100|sortable=yes}}\n| Distances along meridians are conserved, as is distance along one or two standard parallels.<ref>{{cite web |last=Furuti |first=Carlos A. |title= Conic Projections: Equidistant Conic Projections |url=http://www.progonos.com/furuti/MapProj/Normal/ProjCon/projCon.html#EqdCon |access-date=February 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130154139/http://www.progonos.com/furuti/MapProj/Normal/ProjCon/projCon.html#EqdCon |archive-date=December 20, 2013 |url-status=usurped}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Lambert conformal conic projection|Lambert conformal conic]]\n| [[File:Lambert conformal conic projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Conic\n| Conformal\n| [[Johann Heinrich Lambert]]\n| 1772\n| Used in aviation charts.\n|-\n| [[Albers conic projection|Albers conic]]\n| [[File:Albers projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Conic\n| Equal-area\n| [[Heinrich C. Albers]]\n| 1805\n| Two standard parallels with low distortion between them.\n|-\n| [[Werner projection|Werner]]\n| [[File:Werner projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoconical\n| Equal-area, equidistant\n| [[Johannes Stabius]]\n| {{Circa|1500|sortable=yes}}\n| Parallels are equally spaced concentric circular arcs. Distances from the [[North Pole]] are correct as are the curved distances along parallels and distances along central meridian.\n|-\n| [[Bonne projection|Bonne]]\n| [[File:Bonne projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoconical, cordiform\n| Equal-area\n| [[Bernardus Sylvanus]]\n| 1511\n| Parallels are equally spaced concentric circular arcs and standard lines. Appearance depends on reference parallel. General case of both Werner and sinusoidal.\n|-\n| [[Bottomley projection|Bottomley]]\n| [[File:Bottomley projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Pseudoconical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Henry Bottomley]]\n| 2003\n| Alternative to the Bonne projection with simpler overall shape<br/>\nParallels are elliptical arcs<br/>Appearance depends on reference parallel.\n|-\n| [[Polyconic projection|American polyconic]]\n| [[File:American Polyconic projection.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoconical\n| Compromise\n| [[Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler]]\n| {{Circa|1820|sortable=yes}}\n| Distances along the parallels are preserved as are distances along the central meridian.\n|-\n| [[Rectangular polyconic projection|Rectangular polyconic]]\n| [[File:Rectangular polyconic projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoconical\n| Compromise\n| [[U.S. Coast Survey]]\n| {{Circa|1853|sortable=yes}}\n| Latitude along which scale is correct can be chosen. Parallels meet meridians at right angles.\n|-\n|  [[Latitudinally equal-differential polyconic projection|Latitudinally equal-differential polyconic]]\n|\n| Pseudoconical\n| Compromise\n| China State Bureau of Surveying and Mapping\n| 1963\n| Polyconic: parallels are non-concentric arcs of circles.\n|-\n| [[Nicolosi globular projection|Nicolosi globular]]\n| [[File:Nicolosi globular projections SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoconical<ref>\n[http://www.csiss.org/map-projections/Polyconic/Nicolosi_Globular.pdf \"Nicolosi Globular projection\"]\n</ref>\n|Compromise\n| [[Al-Biruni|Ab\u016b Ray\u1e25\u0101n al-B\u012br\u016bn\u012b]]; reinvented by Giovanni Battista Nicolosi, 1660.<ref name=\"SnyderFlattening\"/>{{rp|14}}\n| {{Circa|1000|sortable=yes}}\n|\n|- id=\"azimuthal\"\n| [[Azimuthal equidistant projection|Azimuthal equidistant]]<br/><small>=Postel<br/>=zenithal equidistant</small>\n| [[File:Azimuthal equidistant projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Azimuthal\n| Equidistant\n| [[Ab\u016b Ray\u1e25\u0101n al-B\u012br\u016bn\u012b]]\n| {{Circa|1000|sortable=yes}}\n| Distances from center are conserved.<br/>\nUsed as the emblem of the United Nations, extending to 60\u00b0 S.\n|-\n| [[Gnomonic projection|Gnomonic]]\n| [[File:Gnomonic projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Azimuthal\n| Gnomonic\n| [[Thales]] (possibly)\n| data-sort-value=-580 | {{Circa|580&nbsp;BC}}\n| All great circles map to straight lines. Extreme distortion far from the center. Shows less than one hemisphere.\n|-\n| [[Lambert azimuthal equal-area projection|Lambert azimuthal equal-area]]\n| [[File:Lambert azimuthal equal-area projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Azimuthal\n| Equal-area\n| [[Johann Heinrich Lambert]]\n| 1772\n| The straight-line distance between the central point on the map to any other point is the same as the straight-line 3D distance through the globe between the two points.\n|-\n| [[Stereographic projection#Applications to other disciplines|Stereographic]]\n| [[File:Stereographic projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Azimuthal\n| Conformal\n| [[Hipparchos]]*\n| data-sort-value=-200 | {{Circa|200&nbsp;BC}}\n| Map is infinite in extent with outer hemisphere inflating severely, so it is often used as two hemispheres. Maps all small circles to circles, which is useful for planetary mapping to preserve the shapes of craters.\n|-\n| [[Orthographic projection in cartography|Orthographic]]\n| [[File:Orthographic projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Azimuthal\n| Perspective\n| [[Hipparchos]]*\n| data-sort-value=-200 | {{Circa|200&nbsp;BC}}\n| View from an infinite distance.\n|-\n| [[General Perspective projection|Vertical perspective]]\n| [[File:Vertical perspective SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Azimuthal\n| Perspective\n| Matthias Seutter*\n| 1740\n| View from a finite distance. Can only display less than a hemisphere.\n|-\n| [[two-point equidistant projection|Two-point equidistant]]\n| [[File:Two-point equidistant projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Azimuthal\n| Equidistant\n| Hans Maurer\n| 1919\n| Two \"control points\" can be almost arbitrarily chosen. The two straight-line distances from any point on the map to the two control points are correct.\n|-\n| [[Peirce quincuncial projection|Peirce quincuncial]]\n| [[File:Peirce quincuncial projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Other\n| Conformal\n| [[Charles Sanders Peirce]]\n| 1879\n| Tessellates. Can be tiled continuously on a plane, with edge-crossings matching except for four singular points per tile.\n|-\n| [[Guyou hemisphere-in-a-square projection]]\n| [[File:guyou doubly periodic projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Other\n| Conformal\n| [[\u00c9mile Guyou]]\n| 1887\n| Tessellates.\n|-\n| [[Adams hemisphere-in-a-square projection]]\n| [[File:Adams hemisphere in a square.JPG|150px]]\n| Other\n| Conformal\n| [[Oscar Sherman Adams]]\n| 1925\n|\n|-\n| [[Lee Conformal Projection|Lee conformal world on a tetrahedron]]\n| [[File:Lee Conformal World in a Tetrahedron projection.png|150px]]\n| Polyhedral\n| Conformal\n| [[L. P. Lee]]\n| 1965\n| Projects the globe onto a regular tetrahedron. Tessellates.\n|-\n| [[AuthaGraph projection]]\n| [[:File:Authagraph projection.jpg|Link to file]]<!--Note: The reason this file is being linked is because it is licensed as non-free content. Each use of non-free content must comply with Wikipedia's non-free content use policy (WP:NFCCP) and this file's use in this particular article does not. If you want to use the file here, you need to provide a valid non-free use rationale for this particular use. Please be advised, however, that this can be difficult to do per WP:NFLISTS and No. 6 of WP:NFC#UUI. Questions about this can be asked at WP:MCQ. -->\n| Polyhedral\n| Compromise\n|[[Hajime Narukawa]]\n| 1999\n| Approximately equal-area. Tessellates.\n|-\n| [[Octant projection]]\n| [[File:Leonardo da Vinci\u2019s Mappamundi.jpg|150px]]\n| Polyhedral\n| Compromise\n|[[Leonardo da Vinci]]\n| 1514\n| Projects the globe onto eight octants ([[Reuleaux triangle]]s) with no meridians and no parallels.\n|-\n| [[Cahill's butterfly map]]\n| [[File:Cahill Butterfly Map.jpg|150px]]\n| Polyhedral\n| Compromise\n|[[Bernard J. S. Cahill|Bernard Joseph Stanislaus Cahill]]\n| 1909\n| Projects the globe onto an octahedron with symmetrical components and contiguous landmasses that may be displayed in various arrangements.\n|-\n| [[Cahill\u2013Keyes projection]]\n| [[File:Cahill-Keyes projection.png|150px]]\n| Polyhedral\n| Compromise\n|[[Gene Keyes]]\n| 1975\n| Projects the globe onto a truncated octahedron with symmetrical components and contiguous land masses that may be displayed in various arrangements.\n|-\n| [[Waterman butterfly projection]]\n| [[File:Waterman projection.png|150px]]\n| Polyhedral\n| Compromise\n| [[Steve Waterman (mathematician)|Steve Waterman]]\n| 1996\n| Projects the globe onto a truncated octahedron with symmetrical components and contiguous land masses that may be displayed in various arrangements.\n|-\n| [[Quadrilateralized spherical cube]]\n|\n| Polyhedral\n| Equal-area\n| F. Kenneth Chan, E. M. O'Neill\n| 1973\n|\n|-\n| [[Dymaxion map]]\n| [[File:Dymaxion projection.png|150px]]\n| Polyhedral\n| Compromise\n| [[Buckminster Fuller]]\n| 1943\n| Also known as a Fuller Projection.\n|-\n| [[Myriahedral projection]]s\n|\n| Polyhedral\n| Compromise\n| [[Jarke J. van Wijk]]\n| 2008\n| Projects the globe onto a myriahedron: a polyhedron with a very large number of faces.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jarke J. van Wijk|title=Unfolding the Earth: Myriahedral Projections|url=http://www.win.tue.nl/~vanwijk/myriahedral/}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Carlos A. Furuti|title=Interrupted Maps: Myriahedral Maps|url=http://www.progonos.com/furuti/MapProj/Normal/ProjInt/projInt.html#MyriahedralMaps}}\n</ref>\n|-\n| [[Craig retroazimuthal projection|Craig retroazimuthal]]<br/><small>= Mecca</small>\n| [[File:Craig projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Retroazimuthal\n| Compromise\n| James Ireland Craig\n| 1909\n|\n|-\n| [[Hammer retroazimuthal projection|Hammer retroazimuthal, front hemisphere]]\n| [[File:Hammer retroazimuthal projection front SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Retroazimuthal\n|\n| [[Ernst Hammer (cartographer)|Ernst Hammer]]\n| 1910\n|\n|-\n| [[Hammer retroazimuthal projection|Hammer retroazimuthal, back hemisphere]]\n| [[File:Hammer retroazimuthal projection back SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Retroazimuthal\n|\n| [[Ernst Hammer (cartographer)|Ernst Hammer]]\n| 1910\n|\n|-\n| [[Littrow projection|Littrow]]\n| [[File:Littrow projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Retroazimuthal\n| Conformal\n| [[Joseph Johann Littrow]]\n| 1833\n| on equatorial aspect it shows a hemisphere except for poles.\n|-\n| [[armadillo projection|Armadillo]]\n| [[File:Armadillo projection SW.JPG|150px]]\n| Other\n| Compromise\n| [[Erwin Raisz]]\n| 1943\n|\n|-\n| [[GS50 projection|GS50]]\n| [[File:GS50 projection.png|150px]]\n| Other\n| Conformal\n| [[John P. Snyder]]\n| 1982\n| Designed specifically to minimize distortion when used to display all 50 [[U.S. state]]s.\n|-\n| Wagner VII<br/><small>= Hammer-Wagner</small>\n| [[File:Wagner-VII world map projection.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudoazimuthal\n| Equal-area\n| K. H. Wagner\n| 1941\n| \n|-\n| Atlantis<br/><small>= Transverse Mollweide</small>\n| [[File:Atlantis-landscape.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| John Bartholomew\n| 1948\n| Oblique version of Mollweide\n|-\n| Bertin<br/><small>= Bertin-Rivi\u00e8re<br/> = Bertin 1953</small>\n| [[File:Bertin-map.jpg|150px]]\n| Other\n| Compromise\n| Jacques Bertin\n| 1953\n| Projection in which the compromise is no longer homogeneous but instead is modified for a larger deformation of the oceans, to achieve lesser deformation of the continents. Commonly used for French geopolitical maps.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://visionscarto.net/bertin-projection-1953 |title=Bertin Projection (1953) |access-date=January 27, 2020 |last=Rivi\u00e8re |first=Philippe |date=October 1, 2017 |work=visionscarto |publisher= |location= |language= |quote= }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>The first known popularizer/user and not necessarily the creator.\n\n==Key==\n{{Main|Map projection}}\n\n===Type of projection===\n; Cylindrical: In standard presentation, these map regularly-spaced meridians to equally spaced vertical lines, and parallels to horizontal lines.\n; Pseudocylindrical: In standard presentation, these map the central meridian and parallels as straight lines. Other meridians are curves (or possibly straight from pole to equator), regularly spaced along parallels.\n; Conic: In standard presentation, conic (or conical) projections map meridians as straight lines, and parallels as arcs of circles.\n; Pseudoconical: In standard presentation, pseudoconical projections represent the central meridian as a straight line, other meridians as complex curves, and parallels as circular arcs.\n; Azimuthal: In standard presentation, azimuthal projections map meridians as straight lines and parallels as complete, concentric circles. They are radially symmetrical. In any presentation (or aspect), they preserve directions from the center point. This means great circles through the central point are represented by straight lines on the map.\n; Pseudoazimuthal: In standard presentation, pseudoazimuthal projections map the equator and central meridian to perpendicular, intersecting straight lines. They map parallels to complex curves bowing away from the equator, and meridians to complex curves bowing in toward the central meridian. Listed here after pseudocylindrical as generally similar to them in shape and purpose.\n; Other: Typically calculated from formula, and not based on a particular projection\n; Polyhedral maps: Polyhedral maps can be folded up into a polyhedral approximation to the sphere, using particular projection to map each face with low distortion.\n\n===Properties===\n; Conformal: Preserves angles locally, implying that local shapes are not distorted and that local scale is constant in all directions from any chosen point.\n; Equal-area: Area measure is conserved everywhere.\n; Compromise: Neither conformal nor equal-area, but a balance intended to reduce overall distortion.\n; Equidistant: All distances from one (or two) points are correct. Other equidistant properties are mentioned in the notes.\n; Gnomonic: All great circles are straight lines.\n; Retroazimuthal: Direction to a fixed location B (by the shortest route) corresponds to the direction on the map from A to B.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Snyder |first=John P. |author-link=John P. Snyder |year=1987 |title=Map projections \u2013 A working manual |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |series=U.S. Geological Survey Professional Paper |volume=1395 |publication-place=Washington, D.C. |url=https://pubs.usgs.gov/pp/1395/report.pdf |accessdate=2019-02-18 |doi=10.3133/pp1395}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Snyder |first1=John P. |author-link1=John P. Snyder |last2=Voxland |first2=Philip M. |title=An Album of Map Projections |series=U.S. Geological Survey Professional Paper|volume= 1453 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |publication-place=Washington, D.C. |url=http://pubs.usgs.gov/pp/1453/report.pdf |year=1989 |accessdate=2019-02-18 |doi=10.3133/pp1453}}\n\n{{Map projections}}\n\n[[Category:Map projections| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dynamic list}}\n\nThis is a summary of [[map projection]]s that have articles of their own on Wikipedia or that are otherwise [[WP:NOTABLE|notable]]. Because there is no limit to the number of possible map projections,<ref name=\"SnyderFlattening\">\n{{cite book\n| author=Snyder, John P.\n| title=Flattening the earth: two thousand years of map projections\n| publisher =[[University of Chicago Press]]\n| year=1993\n| isbn =0-226-76746-9\n| page=1}}\n</ref> there can be no comprehensive list.\n\n==Table of projections==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Projection\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n! Type\n! Properties\n! Creator\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Year\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|- id=\"cylindrical\"\n| [[Equirectangular projection|Equirectangular]] <br/><small>= equidistant cylindrical<br/> = rectangular<br/> = la carte parall\u00e9logrammatique</small>\n| [[File:Equirectangular projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equidistant\n| [[Marinus of Tyre]]\n| {{Circa|120|sortable=yes}}\n| Simplest geometry; distances along meridians are conserved.<br/>\n[[Plate carr\u00e9e projection|Plate carr\u00e9e]]: special case having the equator as the standard parallel.\n|-\n| [[Cassini projection|Cassini]] <br/><small>= Cassini\u2013Soldner</small>\n| [[File:Cassini projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equidistant\n| [[C\u00e9sar-Fran\u00e7ois Cassini de Thury]]\n| 1745\n| Transverse of equidistant projection; distances along central meridian are conserved.<br/>Distances perpendicular to central meridian are preserved.\n|-\n| [[Mercator projection|Mercator]]<br/><small>= Wright</small>\n| [[File:Mercator projection Square.JPG|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Conformal\n| [[Gerardus Mercator]]\n| 1569\n| Lines of constant bearing (rhumb lines) are straight, aiding navigation. Areas inflate with latitude, becoming so extreme that the map cannot show the poles.\n|-\n| [[Web Mercator]]\n| [[File:Web maps Mercator projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Google]]\n| 2005\n| Variant of [[Mercator projection|Mercator]] that ignores Earth's ellipticity for fast calculation, and clips latitudes to ~85.05\u00b0 for square presentation. De facto standard for Web mapping applications.\n|-\n| [[Transverse Mercator projection#Ellipsoidal transverse Mercator|Gauss\u2013Kr\u00fcger]]<br/><small>= Gauss conformal<br/>= (ellipsoidal) transverse Mercator</small>\n| [[File:Ellipsoidal transverse Mercator projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Conformal\n| [[Carl Friedrich Gauss]]\n[[Johann Heinrich Louis Kr\u00fcger]]\n| 1822\n| This transverse, ellipsoidal form of the Mercator is finite, unlike  the equatorial Mercator. Forms the basis of the [[Universal Transverse Mercator coordinate system]].\n|-\n| [[Roussilhe oblique stereographic projection|Roussilhe oblique stereographic]]\n|\n|\n|\n| Henri Roussilhe\n| 1922\n|\n|-\n|Hotine oblique Mercator\n|[[File:Hotine Mercator projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n|Cylindrical\n|Conformal\n|M. Rosenmund, J. Laborde, Martin Hotine\n|1903\n|\n|-\n| [[Gall stereographic projection|Gall stereographic]]<br/>\n| [[File:Gall Stereographic projection SW centered.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[James Gall]]\n| 1855\n| Intended to resemble the Mercator while also displaying the poles. Standard parallels at 45\u00b0N/S.\n|-\n| [[Miller projection|Miller]]<br/><small>= Miller cylindrical</small>\n| [[File:Miller projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Compromise\n| [[Osborn Maitland Miller]]\n| 1942\n| Intended to resemble the Mercator while also displaying the poles.\n|-\n| [[Lambert cylindrical equal-area projection|Lambert cylindrical equal-area]]\n| [[File:Lambert cylindrical equal-area projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Johann Heinrich Lambert]]\n| 1772\n| Standard parallel at the equator. Aspect ratio of \u03c0 (3.14). Base projection of the [[cylindrical equal-area projection|cylindrical equal-area]] family.\n|-\n| [[Behrmann projection|Behrmann]]\n| [[File:Behrmann projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Walter Behrmann]]\n| 1910\n| Horizontally compressed version of the Lambert equal-area. Has standard parallels at 30\u00b0N/S and an aspect ratio of 2.36.\n|-\n| [[Hobo\u2013Dyer projection|Hobo\u2013Dyer]]\n| [[File:Hobo\u2013Dyer projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[Mick Dyer]]\n| 2002\n| Horizontally compressed version of the Lambert equal-area. Very similar are Trystan Edwards and Smyth equal surface (= Craster rectangular) projections with standard parallels at around 37\u00b0N/S. Aspect ratio of ~2.0.\n|-\n| [[Gall\u2013Peters projection|Gall\u2013Peters]]<br/><small>= Gall orthographic<br/>= Peters</small>\n| [[File:Gall\u2013Peters projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Equal-area\n| [[James Gall]]\n([[Arno Peters]])\n| 1855\n| Horizontally compressed version of the Lambert equal-area. Standard parallels at 45\u00b0N/S. Aspect ratio of ~1.6. Similar is Balthasart projection with standard parallels at 50\u00b0N/S.\n|-\n| [[Central cylindrical projection|Central cylindrical]]\n| [[File:Central cylindric projection square.JPG|150px]]\n| Cylindrical\n| Perspective\n| (unknown)\n| {{Circa|1850|sortable=yes}}\n| Practically unused in cartography because of severe polar distortion, but popular in [[panoramic photography]], especially for architectural scenes.\n|- id=\"pseudocylindrical\"\n| [[Sinusoidal projection|Sinusoidal]]<br/><small>= Sanson\u2013Flamsteed<br/>= Mercator equal-area</small>\n| [[File:Sinusoidal projection SW.jpg|150px]]\n| Pseudocylindrical\n| Equal-area, equidistant\n| (Several; first is unknown)\n| {{Circa|1600|sortable=yes}}\n| Meridians are sinusoids; parallels are equally space